  "prompt": "Can an isosceles triangle be a right triangle? Why or why not?",
  "response": "Yes, an **isosceles triangle can be a right triangle**. Here's why:\n\n### Definitions:\n1. **Isosceles Triangle**: A triangle with at least two sides of equal length.\n2. **Right Triangle**: A triangle that has one angle exactly equal to 90 degrees.\n\n### Combining Both:\nFor a triangle to be both isosceles and right-angled, it must satisfy both conditions simultaneously. Here's how:\n\n- **Equal Legs**: In an isosceles right triangle, the two legs (the sides that form the right angle) are of equal length.\n- **Angles**: The triangle has one right angle (90 degrees) and the other two angles are each 45 degrees. This is because the sum of angles in any triangle is 180 degrees:\n  \\[\n  90^\\circ + 45^\\circ + 45^\\circ = 180^\\circ\n  \\]\n  \n### Example:\nImagine a triangle where both legs are 1 unit long and meet at a right angle. The hypotenuse (the side opposite the right angle) can be calculated using the Pythagorean theorem:\n\\[\n\\text{Hypotenuse} = \\sqrt{1^2 + 1^2} = \\sqrt{2}\n\\]\nThis triangle has:\n- Two sides of equal length (1 unit each)\n- One right angle (90 degrees)\n- Two base angles of 45 degrees each\n\n### Visualization:\n```\n       /|\n      / |\n     /  |\n    /   |\n   /____|\n```\nIn the above diagram:\n- The two legs are equal.\n- The angle between them is 90 degrees.\n\n### Conclusion:\nAn isosceles right triangle is a valid and common type of triangle in geometry. It combines the properties of both isosceles and right triangles, making it a useful shape in various mathematical applications and real-world scenarios.",
